607.answer:
Callback hell is deep nesting of anonymous callbacks that makes flow hard to follow. Refactoring extracts each callback into a named function while keeping the callback-based API.

Before (nested callbacks):
```javascript
function loadUserDashboard(userId, callback) {
  getUser(userId, function(err, user) {
    if (err) return callback(err);
    getPosts(user.id, function(err, posts) {
      if (err) return callback(err);
      getComments(posts[0].id, function(err, comments) {
        if (err) return callback(err);
        callback(null, { user, posts, comments });
      });
    });
  });
}
```

After (named helper callbacks):
```javascript
function loadUserDashboard(userId, callback) {
  getUser(userId, onUserLoaded);

  function onUserLoaded(err, user) {
    if (err) return callback(err);
    getPosts(user.id, onPostsLoaded.bind(null, user));
  }

  function onPostsLoaded(user, err, posts) {
    if (err) return callback(err);
    getComments(posts[0].id, onCommentsLoaded.bind(null, user, posts));
  }

  function onCommentsLoaded(user, posts, err, comments) {
    if (err) return callback(err);
    callback(null, { user, posts, comments });
  }
}
```

Key changes: each anonymous callback is replaced with a named inner function. The nesting is eliminated — all helpers are at the same indentation level. The external API (callback-based) is unchanged.

